### Step 4: Snapshot source Elasticsearch

  - Port forward the source `aws-es-proxy-service` 

  ```
  kubectl \
    -n [your namespace] \
    port-forward \
    svc/aws-es-proxy-service 9200:9200
  ```

  - Register the snapshot repository inside Elasticsearch cluster via the [ES API](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/rest-apis.html). 
    
    In this guide, same bucket is used with multiple domains. Hence adding a basepath will keeps the snapshots in separate directories.

    A sample template is given below:

  ```
    PUT http://localhost:9200/_snapshot/<repo-name-for-snapshot>
  {
    "type": "s3",
    "settings": {
      "bucket": "<s3-bucket for snapshots>",
      "base_path": "<repo-name for snapshot>",
      "region": "eu-west-2",
      "role_arn": "<role arn from es_snapshots_role secret>"
    }
  }
  ```

  - Create a snapshot 

  ```
  PUT http://localhost:9200/_snapshot/<repo-name-for-snapshot>/latest-snapshot
  ```

### Step 5: Restore to encrypted Elasticsearch

  - Port forward the encrypted Elasticsearch cluster

  ```
  kubectl \
    -n [your namespace] \
    port-forward \
    svc/aws-es-proxy-service-encrypted 9200:9200
  ```

  - Restore snapshot

  NOTE: `"include_global_state":true` will restore all the key data

  ```
  POST http://localhost:9200/_snapshot/<repo-name-for-snapshot>/<snapshot-you-want-to-restore-from>/_restore
  {
    "include_global_state": true
  }
  ```

